 of Gaelic surnames based on the personal name <i>Aodh</i> ‘fire’, for example <b>Ó hAodha</b>, <b>Mac Aodha</b>; see   McCoy   and compare   McHugh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hughs","meanings":["English: variant of   Hughes  ."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]},{"name":"Hewes","meanings":["English (Essex):","variant of   Hughes  .","variant of   Hawes  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ralph Hughes was born in 1227, in Challcombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom as the son of Henry de Hughes II and Mrs Unknown. He had at least 4 sons and 2 daughters with Alice de Beaumont. He died in 1283, in his hometown, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1227–1283":"1227–1283","1230–Fem